Introduction¶

This dataset collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. The original source of the dataset is Kaggle. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row.

There are 1 dependent variable (No-show) and 13 independent variables (PatientId, AppointmentID, Gender, ScheduledDay, AppointmentDay, Age, Neighbourhood, Scholarship, Hipertension, Diabetes, Alcoholism, Handcap, SMS_received).

Description of the Dataset's Features:¶

  • PatientId: A number to identify the patient.
  • AppointmentID: A number to identify the appointment
  • Gender: The gender of the patient. M: Male or F: Female.
  • ScheduledDay: The date where the patient set up their appointment.
  • AppointmentDay: The date of the appointment.
  • Age: The age of the patient.
  • Neighbourhood: The location of the hospital.
  • Scholarship: An integer value that indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Famlia. 1: True or 0: False
  • Hipertension: A integer value that indicates whether or not the patient has hipertensin. 1: True or 0: False
  • Diabetes: A integer value that indicates whether or not the patient has diabetes. 1: True or 0: False
  • Alcoholism: A integer value that indicates whether or not the patient is alcoholic. 1: True or 0: False
  • Handcap: A number of disabilities the patient has.
  • SMS_received: A integer value that indicates whether or not the patient received an SMS message. 1: True or 0: False
  • No-show: Indicates whether or not the patient showed up for their appointment. No: the patient showed up to their appointment or Yes: the patient did not show up.

Questions¶

  • Do patients who are enrolled in the Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Famlia are more likely to show up for their scheduled appointment?
  • Does the SMS messages affect the patients' attendance for their scheduled appointment?
  • Which appointment month has the most not attended appointments rate?
  • What is the most month that patients call to schedule their appointments?
  • Which gender usually attends their scheduled appointment?
  • Is there a relation between the number of disabilities and the patients not showing up to their scheduled appointment?
  • Does the location of the hospital has an impact on patients not showing up for their scheduled appointment?
  • What is the most disease that absent patients have?

After some investigation, the dataset creator, Joni Hoppen, stated that the 'Handcap' refers to the number of disabilities a person has. For example, if the person is blind and can't walk, the total is 2. (Here is the discussion)

In [471]:
# Check if the age has negative values (invalid values)
df.query('Age < 0')
Out[471]:
PatientId AppointmentID Gender ScheduledDay AppointmentDay Age Neighbourhood Scholarship Hipertension Diabetes Alcoholism Handcap SMS_received No-show
99832 4.659432e+14 5775010 F 2016-06-06T08:58:13Z 2016-06-06T00:00:00Z -1 ROMO 0 0 0 0 0 0 No

There are only one negative value.

Observations:¶

  • This dataset has no null data.
  • This dataset has no duplicate rows.
  • The Age variable has one negative value that needs to be dropped.
  • Some data types need to be changed.
    • PatientId and AppointmentID need to be changed to a string, since they are an ID number (they have no numerical meaning).
    • ScheduledDay and AppointmentDay need to be changed to a date instead of strings.
    • Scholarship, Hipertension, Diabetes, Alcoholism, SMS_received, and No-show should be changed to boolean.

Research Question 1: Do patients who enrolled in the Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Família are more likely to show up for their scheduled appointment?¶

To compare the two values, let's find the percentage of each. Reference

In [484]:

Now, let's compare them using matplotlib bar chart.

In [487]:
ind = np.arange(len(no_scholarship_show))  # the x locations for the groups
width = 0.35       # the width of the bars

# plot bars
no_scholarship_bars = plt.bar(ind, no_scholarship_show, width, color='g', alpha=.7, label='Have Scholarship')
have_scholarship_bars = plt.bar(ind + width, have_scholarship_show, width, color='r', alpha=.7, label='No Scholarship')

# title and labels
plt.ylabel('Percentage')
plt.xlabel('Attendance')
plt.title('Percentage by Scholarship and Attendance')
locations = ind + width / 2  # xtick locations
labels = ['Attended', 'Absent']  # xtick labels
plt.xticks(locations, labels)

# legend
plt.legend();
  • The percentage of attended patients who are enrolled in the Brasilian Welfare Program is higher than the attended patients who are not enrolled in the Brasilian Welfare Program.
  • The percentage of absent patients who are enrolled in the Brasilian Welfare Program is lower than the absent patients who are not enrolled in the Brasilian Welfare Program.

To see if the location of the hospital has an impact on patients not showing up for their scheduled appointment, we need to calculate the percentage change between the attended patient and the asbsent ones.

I found that there's a Panda's function to calculate the percentage change pct_change() but it doesn't work if I want to compare two specific different columns, so I looked up this issue and found a solution in StackOverflow by using a user-defined funtion.

In [517]:
# The function below calculates the percentage change of two different columns. 
# Reference: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/42100058/percentage-difference-between-any-two-columns-of-pandas-dataframe
def percentage_change(col1,col2):
    return ((col2 - col1) / col1) * 100

# Call the function to calculate the percentage difference between the attended neighbourhoods and the absent neighbourhoods.
percentage_change(df.Neighbourhood[attended].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100,df.Neighbourhood[absent].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100)

Conclusions¶

Do patients who are enrolled in the Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Famlia are more likely to show up for their scheduled appointment?

  • Patients who are enrolled in the Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Famlia are more likely to show up for their scheduled appointment.

Does the SMS messages affect the patients' attendance for their scheduled appointment?

  • Patients who received an SMS message are more likely to show up for their scheduled appointment.

Which appointment month has the most not attended appointments rate?

  • Patients tend to schedule their appointment in May.
  • Patients who have an appointment in May are more likely to not show up for their scheduled appointment.
  • Patients who have an appointment in June are more likely to not show up for their scheduled appointment.

What is the most month that patients call to schedule their appointments?

  • Patients tend to contact hospitals to schedule an appointment in May more than other months, which is the same day as their actual appointment.

Which gender usually attends their scheduled appointment?

  • Female patients are more likely to show up for their scheduled appointment than male patients.

Is there a relation between the number of disabilities and the patients not showing up to their scheduled appointment?

  • There is no relation between the number of disabilities and the patients not showing up to their scheduled appointment, however; patients with no disabilities are more likely to schedule an appointment.

Does the location of the hospital has an impact on patients not showing up for their scheduled appointment?

  • Hospitals located in 'ILHA DO BOI' have more no-show appointments than other hospitals.
  • Hospitals located in 'SANTOS DUMONT' have fewer no-show appointments than other hospitals.

What is the most disease that absent patients have?

  • Patients who suffer from hypertension are more likely to not show up for their scheduled appointment.
  • Patients who have diabetes are slightly more likely to not show up for their scheduled appointment.
  • Alcoholism has no effect on patients' attendance at their appointment.

Limitations¶

  • I believe that if the dataset has more data for, at least, a whole year (12 months), the results will be more accurate and can give us new questions and insights. For example, which month is the most fully booked month in the year? Do patients tend to schedule appointments in summer more than in other seasons?
  • If the 'Handcap' feature is more specific of the disability type instead of only numbers, it will be more helpful and can lead to new questions and insights too.
  • If the 'Handcap' feature is more specific of the disability type instead of only numbers, it will be more helpful and can lead to new questions and insights too.
  • If the 'SMS_received' feature has more information, like the date of sending the SMS message and the number of SMS messages sent, it may help in showing more impact on the patients' attendance. Also, we can explore more in this area and discover new findings.
